title: Improve performance of Pad CUDA kernel
body:
**Description**: 

Most image models use the `Pad` operation to pad only along the `height` and `width` dimensions (i.e.) they convert tensors of shape [N, C, H, W] to [N, C, H + pad_h, W +pad_w]. Our current implementation for Pad in CUDA is too "generic" (processes N-D tensors accounting for possible padding in all dims) to optimally process this often-occurring use-case. This change adds logic to recognize this special case and adds a specialized implementation (Torch-inspired) for the same.

This change closes the gap with Torch for model in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166. These gains should be applicable to all image models using such padding patterns.

The existing unit tests for Pad are very exhaustive and there are a good number of tests using the new specialized code path. No new unit tests required for this change. 

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166
Possibly provides good gains for models in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8362 and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7681 (they are encouraged to try with this commit)

title: Dimension with zero size raises Reshape error
body:
**Describe the bug**
When indexing into a tensor to update (`ScatterND`), an implicit reshape is called on the `updates` tensor to add an extra dimension, this Reshape causes an error to be raised when the final dim in the `updates` tensor has size zero.

```
onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.RuntimeException: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 6 : RUNTIME_EXCEPTION : Non-zero status code returned while running Reshape node. Name:'Reshape_70' Status Message: 
/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/reshape_helper.h:27 onnxruntime::ReshapeHelper::ReshapeHelper(const onnxruntime::TensorShape&, std::vector<long int>&, bool) i < input_shape.NumDimensions() was false. 
The dimension with value zero exceeds the dimension size of the input tensor.
```

It is very clear why this error is being raised [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/reshape_helper.h#L25), in my example below the input_shape is `(2, 0)`, the requested shape is `(1, 2, 0)` and it doesn't like the fact that a dim of zero size exists in a position > number of dims in input_shape. My question is **why does this check exist**? This works fine in PyTorch (presumably resulting in a no-op).


**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 16.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.0
- Python version: 3.8


**To Reproduce**
```py
    import torch
    import onnxruntime as ort

    class Model(torch.nn.Module):

        def forward(self, x, y):
            x[0,:,:y.shape[1]] = y
            return x

    model = torch.jit.script(Model())
    x, y = torch.randn(2,2,2), torch.randn(2,1)
    output = model(x,y)
    torch.onnx.export(model, (x,y), "tmp.onnx", input_names=["x","y"], dynamic_axes={"y":[1]},
    example_outputs=output, opset_version=13, verbose=True)

    sess = ort.InferenceSession("tmp.onnx")
    # THIS WORKS
    y= torch.randn(2,1)
    print(sess.run(None, {"x": x.numpy(), "y": y.numpy()}))
    # THS FAILS
    y= torch.randn(2,0)
    print(sess.run(None, {"x": x.numpy(), "y": y.numpy()}))
```

**Expected behavior**
No error to be raised, the reshape works correctly as per PyTorch.

My current solution is to add conditionals that check the `numel()` of the incoming tensor > 0 before peforming the update, but ideally I shouldn't have to do this. Can I rewrite the update in a cleaner way to avoid the error?

title: Update GetEnvironmentVar() to return optional value.
body:
**Description**
Update existing GetEnvironmentVar() function:
- return an optional value to distinguish between a variable with an empty string value and an undefined variable
- move out of Env class to minimize dependencies (e.g., MLAS may depend on Env and our optional type currently uses a third-party library. this way, MLAS doesn't need to also depend on it.)

The original GetEnvironmentVar() is renamed GetEnvironmentVarOrEmpty() to reflect its behavior of returning an empty string for undefined variables. Most call sites were updated to use this renamed version to minimize behavior changes.

**Motivation and Context**
I am considering using an environment variable to represent a list of ops where an empty string value is valid.
This change enables that. It touches quite a few files so I'm doing it separately.

title: Make some common macros safer to use.
body:
**Description**
Some macros were defined like this: `#define MACRO(condition, ...) if (condition) do_something`.
This can be problematic if expanded in a context like this:
```
if (condition_1)
  MACRO(condition_2);
else
  // logic for !condition_1
```
The else will associate with MACRO's if and we get unexpected results, e.g., when `condition_1 && !condition_2`.

We can avoid this by wrapping MACRO in `do { ... } while(false)`.

**Motivation and Context**
Clean up code.

title: Add quantization support of GEMM directly with QGemm
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
QGemm takes in quantized A, B, C, and quantization parameters of output Y, in which C and quantization parameters of Y are optional. Its output can be quantized or full precision, which depends on whether quantization parameters of Y exists or not. If quant params of Y are provided, the output will be requantized or is full precision. 

Comparing with QLinearMatMul and MatMulInteger, QGemm supports transpose, apha and beta attribute.

The formula for quantized GEMM is:
Y = alpha * scale_a * scale_b * ((A_int8 - zp_a) * (B_int8 - zp_b) + C_int32), in which,
C_int32 is quantized with formula: C_int32 = (beta * C) / (alpha * scale_a * scale_b)

title: Bug fix for per layer ORTModule wrap in T5
body:
**Description**: when wrapping T5 encoder/decoder by layer, ORTModule throws the error during training:
AssertionError: ORT found the 6-th module output 'output-6' is non-differentiable according to the onnx graph. However, the gradient value is still provided by PyTorch's autograd engine.

**Motivation and Context**
- The issue can be reproduced with 2 layers of encoders/decoders. And it's specific to decoders. Let's say we have two layers of decoders. In forward pass, an output (requires_grad=False) in the first layer becomes the input of second layer. But its requires_grad becomes True, which is inconsistent (thus incorrect) with Torch's behavior. Therefore it's causing the exception above later on in backward pass.

In most cases, this won't happen. But in some cases where the tensor has been manipulated (re-assign, overwritten, etc.) in the first layer, the requires_flag may be assigned to True by default with torch.autograd extension - see Torch's doc for more details - https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/notes/extending.html#extending-torch-autograd .

The solution is to check _graph_info.output_grad_indices_non_differentiable and mark the tensor with correct requires_grad flag by calling mark_non_differentiable() before the outputs returned back to torch.

**Description**: Optimizer variadic elementwise ops

For cases like this, 12 layers, reusing the same weights. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127147598-8c0dd2b8-ebf0-4f45-8b76-9553d6bfad63.png)

In PyTorch, after each PythonOpGrad executes, it will accumulate the grad into a buffer (except the first step), so 11 elementwise operator.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149121-fb62f97a-d9e3-441f-87ea-85d0f59d7223.png)

In ORT, we will do the gradient sum with a Sum operator at the end, check the part the green arrow points to. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149342-9d605708-7338-49d3-80fb-4c089742d35d.png)

If we take a closer look: 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/127149457-4520cbab-8913-4536-ab79-8fda83dc6afb.png)

This is a cuda memset + 12 binary element wise operator. 

Though we could do something to align our scheduling with PyTorch's for better memory usage. But this PR only trying to change "a cuda memset (1.12ms) + 12 binary element wise operator (47.278ms)" to "a cuda memcpy (2.75ms) + 11 binary element wise operator (43.16ms)".e.g. 48.398ms v.s.  45.91ms, 5.14% kernel overhead reduction for this case.

import argparse
import time
import torch
import torch.cuda.profiler
import onnxruntime
import numpy as np


def infer_ort(onnxruntime_session, io_binding):
	onnxruntime_session.run_with_iobinding(io_binding)


def get_model(channels):
	return torch.nn.Conv1d(in_channels=channels, out_channels=channels*2, kernel_size=19,
			stride=2, padding=(1 * 19 // 2), dilation=1, groups=1)


def export_onnx(onnx_path, channels, dtype = torch.float16):
	model = get_model(channels)
	torch.set_grad_enabled(False)
	model.eval()
	model.to('cuda', dtype=dtype)
	waveform_input = torch.rand((4, channels, 128), device='cuda', dtype=dtype)

			onnx_path,
			opset_version=12,
			export_params=True,
			do_constant_folding=True,
			input_names=['input'],
			dynamic_axes=dict(input={
				0: 'B',
				2: 'T'
			})
	)

	## check export correctness
	onnxruntime_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(onnx_path)
